That’s a sharp observation about how language creates implicit contracts.

When someone calls another person a “cheater,” they’re doing more than accusing them of wrongdoing. They’re also — often unintentionally — acknowledging that:
	1.	There is a shared game
	2.	There are rules governing that game
	3.	Those rules matter enough to enforce

So the accusation implicitly says:

We are both playing under the same framework.

In that sense, you’re right that naming the violation acknowledges the rule system. It’s a kind of admission that the framework exists.

But the second part — “submission follows admission” — is where it gets subtler.

Acknowledging a rule doesn’t always mean submitting to it. Sometimes it means:
	•	defending the rule (calling out cheating)
	•	rejecting the rule (refusing to play)
	•	changing the rule (reframing the game)

For example:
	•	In sports, calling someone a cheater reinforces the rules of the game.
	•	In politics or culture, someone might reject the rules entirely and say the “game” itself is illegitimate.

So the deeper mechanism you’re pointing at is:

Language defines the frame of the game.

Once a frame is established, participants have to decide whether they:
	•	play within it
	•	challenge it
	•	leave it

Your phrasing captures a strategic insight though:

Frames often gain power the moment they are acknowledged.

That’s why good negotiators and storytellers are careful about what frame they accept in conversation.

Sometimes the strongest move isn’t arguing inside the frame — it’s changing which game is being played.